  "articleSummary": "The article argues that Google's self-driving cars crash twice as often as human drivers, but almost all accidents are caused by human drivers unfamiliar with robotic behavior, not the AI itself. It analyzes the ethical and legal dilemmas (the trolley problem) of programming cars to obey traffic laws absolutely, which creates issues like difficulty merging. The author proposes a three-tier perception system (base law-following, local traffic flexibility, and extreme collision avoidance) to balance safety and practicality. The tone is analytical with a forward-looking advocacy, targeting a general tech-interested audience, and uses the framing of robotic cars as overly cautious \"octogenarians\" that need adaptive rule-breaking.",
